org.apache.freemarker.core.model.impl

Class SequenceTemplateModelIterator

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.apache.freemarker.core.model.impl.SequenceTemplateModelIterator
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    TemplateModelIterator

    public class SequenceTemplateModelIterator
extends Object
implements TemplateModelIterator
    TemplateIterableModel implementation that can iterate through a TemplateSequenceModel be going through the valid indexes and calling TemplateSequenceModel.get(int) for each. This should only be used if you can be sure that TemplateSequenceModel.get(int) and TemplateCollectionModel.getCollectionSize() is efficient. (TemplateSequenceModel doesn't require that to be efficient, as listing the contents should be done with with TemplateIterableModel.iterator()).

    This class assumes that the sequence doesn't change during iteration (as it's technically impossible to detect if a generic TemplateSequenceModel was changed, similarly as it's impossible for a generic List). The index range is decided when the instance is created, and it simply iterates through the predefined index range. Thus for example, if the sequence length decreases after that, it will return null-s (means missing element) at the end, for the indexes that are now out of bounds.

    • Method Detail

      • next

        public TemplateModel next()
                   throws TemplateException
        Description copied from interface: TemplateModelIterator
        Returns the next item. It must not be called if there are no more items, as the behavior is undefined then (typically, NoSuchElementException or IndexOutOfBoundsException will be thrown, or null will be returned). Hence, you should almost always call TemplateModelIterator.hasNext() before this method, and only call this method if that has returned true. (Note that the implementation still can't assume that TemplateModelIterator.hasNext() is always called before TemplateModelIterator.next(); the caller might knows that there's a next item for a different reason, like already knows the size of the collection.)
